I am looking for series related to the human autoimmune diseases, lupus or multiple sclerosis. Therefore, the organisms should contain Homo sapiens and the title of the series should contain one of multiple sclerosis or lupus. Technology should be Highthroughoutput RNA sequencing and was submitted within the past 10 years.

# Build the SQL query
sql <- paste("SELECT DISTINCT gse.title, gse.gse, gpl.title,", " gse.submission_date,",
    " gse.supplementary_file", "FROM", "  gse JOIN gse_gpl ON gse_gpl.gse=gse.gse",
    "  JOIN gpl ON gse_gpl.gpl=gpl.gpl", "WHERE", "  gpl.organism LIKE '%Homo sapiens%' AND",
    "  gse.title LIKE '%lupus%' OR gse.title LIKE '%multiple sclerosis%' AND", "  gpl.technology LIKE '%high-throughput sequencing%' AND",
    "  gse.submission_date > '2013-01-01'", "  ORDER BY gse.submission_date DESC",
    sep = " ")

# Initiate the query
rs <- DBI::dbGetQuery(con, sql)
dim(rs)

Selected the dataset GSE111972

Description below (Poel 2019)

gseAccession <- "GSE111972"
gse <- GEOquery::getGEO(gseAccession, GSEMatrix = FALSE)
gpl <- names(GEOquery::GPLList(gse))[1]
gplInfo <- GEOquery::Meta(GEOquery::getGEO(gpl))

Introduction

Background

Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic neuroinflammatory autoimmune disease. MS is characterized by demyelination and subsequent formation of lesions through out the central nervous system (CNS). Grey matter (GM) and white matter (WM) lesions in the brain show pathological differences. Microglia are CNS-resident and can function as antigen-presenting cells and phagocytes. Their role in MS is complex and controversial (Luo 2017).

General Experimental Design

In total 31 human microglia samples were analyzed from 10 MS donors (MS), including 5 grey matter and 10 white matter samples, and from 11 non-neurological control donors (CON), including 5 grey matter and 11 white matter samples. From each sample total RNA was extracted.(Poel 2019)

Study objectives

The authors isolated human microglia according to the previously described general experimental design. They suggest that pathological changes in MS tissue may be associated with changes in microglia, leading to lesion initiation. The authors wanted to analyze the transcriptional profile of microglia in the collected samples by RNA-sequencing (Luo 2017). Ultimately, they wanted to discover MS-related changes in microglia between the GM and WM brain regions.

Task 4: Interpret, and document

What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?

The control is the CON patient group that consisted of non-neurological control donors. This group is compared against the MS patient group which consisted of multiple sclerosis patients in two tissues: GM (grey matter) and WM (white matter) from the brain.

Why is the dataset of interest to you?

I am currently conducting a research project for the course IMM450 where I am studying the sex bias in antigen-presenting cells in the mouse model experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis for the human disease multiple sclerosis. While this research project is mainly wet lab, I want to try using bioinformatics to analyze differences in MS.

Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes?

There were no duplicated in the gene IDs in the original data set. This stayed the same when trying to conduct identifier mapping.

How did you handle these?

N/A.

Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols?

No. 

How many outliers were removed?

After filtering the lowly expressed genes, we were left with 15076 genes compared to the original 21283. A total of 6207 genes were removed.

How did you handle replicates?

All replicates for each patient group and tissue were treated as separate samples. The replicates can be sorted by their tissue and their patient_group. In the MDS plot, we can see that the samples mostly cluster together as tissues.

What is the final coverage of your dataset?

The final dataset is made up of:

- 15076 with unique identifiers.

- 31 samples in total.

- 2 patient groups *MS* and *CON*, and 2 tissues *GM*, *WM*.

- 10 MS patients and 11 CON

- 10 replicates for WM in the MS group and 11 replicates in the CON group.

- 5 replicates for GM in both patient groups.
